          "body": "Verse 15 is the structural hinge on which the entire chapter turns. 'Now when Jehoiada reached a ripe old age he died; he was one hundred and thirty years old at his death.' The longevity note (130 years — longer than any patriarch after the flood) functions as a measure of divine favor: this man lived so long that his death is itself a turning point in national history. The burial notice is equally striking: 'they buried him in the city of David among the kings, because he had done well in Israel and to God and His house' (24:16). A priest buried among the kings — the reversal of institutional rank signals the Chronicler's theological verdict. Jehoiada's service to the covenant was kingly in substance even if not in title. The contrast with Joash's eventual burial — also in the city of David, but explicitly 'not in the tombs of the kings' (24:25) — is the chapter's sharpest ironic reversal: the priest receives what the king forfeits. Jonathan Edwards' observation in his treatise on religious affections is pertinent here: the surest test of genuine religion is not its high tide but its staying power when the external supports are removed. Jehoiada was the external support; his death tests what remains."
