          "body": "Verses 17-19 compress what may have been months or years of moral deterioration into a rapid narrative sequence. The officials of Judah approach the king with flattering submission (24:17), and Joash — unmoored without Jehoiada — listens. The result is thoroughgoing apostasy: 'they abandoned the house of the Lord, the God of their fathers, and served the Asherim and the idols' (24:18). The Chronicler's theological comment is immediate: 'wrath came upon Judah and Jerusalem for this their guilt.' But God's response to deserved wrath is first to send prophets (24:19) — a pattern the Chronicler emphasizes throughout his work (cf. 2 Chr. 12:5; 15:2; 20:37; 25:15). Prophetic testimony precedes military judgment. God is not trigger-happy with punishment; He sends messengers, and the people's rejection of those messengers is what removes the final restraint. Zechariah's Spirit-clothed address (24:20) is the last prophetic attempt — 'Why do you transgress the commandments of the Lord and do not prosper? Because you have forsaken the Lord, He has also forsaken you.' The rhetorical question exposes the covenantal logic: transgression and lack of prosperity are connected, not coincidental. But the word goes unheeded, and worse, the messenger is killed."
