          "title": "The murder of Zechariah — ingratitude, blood guilt, and the dying prayer",
          "body": "The stoning of Zechariah son of Jehoiada (24:21) is the chapter's moral nadir. Three details make it damning. First, it occurs 'at the command of the king' — Joash is not merely a passive bystander; he orders the execution. Second, it takes place 'in the court of the house of the Lord' — the precinct whose restoration was the achievement of Jehoiada's life is now defiled by the blood of Jehoiada's son. Third, the Chronicler editorializes directly: 'Joash the king did not remember the kindness which his father Jehoiada had shown him' (24:22). The word for kindness is chesed — covenant loyalty, steadfast love, the same word used of God's faithful covenant love throughout the Psalms. Jehoiada had hidden Joash from Athaliah's purge as an infant, preserved his life, installed him as king, and guided his reign for decades. This is the chesed Joash repays with murder. Jesus references Zechariah's death in Matthew 23:35 as the closing bookend of righteous prophetic blood shed 'from Abel to Zechariah son of Berechiah' — whether identifying the same Zechariah or a later one, the martyrological pattern is the same. Zechariah's dying prayer — 'May the Lord see and avenge!' — is a direct appeal to the divine covenant enforcer, and the narrative structure of 24:23-24 confirms it is answered within a year."
